                "unit": "each",
                "amount": 2,
                "prepNote": "halved lengthways",
                "groupLabel": "For the trivet",
                "isOptional": false,
                "ingredientId": "cmp49f5dq0049rkv4hknkvpff",
                "ingredientSlug": "carrot"
              },
              {
                "name": "Celery",
                "unit": "each",
                "amount": 2,
                "prepNote": "roughly chopped",
                "groupLabel": "For the trivet",
                "isOptional": false,
                "ingredientId": "cmp49f5e9004arkv40g1q6rs7",
                "ingredientSlug": "celery"
              }
            ],
            "defaultServings": 6
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "A roasting rack holds the joint above the pan juices so the underside roasts rather than braises. A V-shaped rack works well for a rolled joint.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Method",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Prepare the joint",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Take the beef out of the fridge an hour before cooking. Pat it dry with kitchen paper. Rub all over with the softened butter, then press in the salt and pepper. If using mustard powder, mix it into the butter first.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Heat the oven to 220 degrees C fan. Scatter the onion, carrot, and celery across the base of the roasting pan. Set the rack on top and place the joint fat-side up on the rack.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Roast and probe",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Roast at 220 degrees C for 20 minutes to ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "sear",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmpsogkob0000f8v4xrkjudnf"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " the surface and colour the crust, then reduce to 180 degrees C. Start checking the internal temperature after another 40 minutes.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Pull the joint when the probe reads 52 degrees C at the thickest part for rare to medium-rare. For medium, wait for 58 degrees C; for well done, 68 degrees C. The temperature rises a few more degrees during resting.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Rest and carve",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Transfer the joint to a warm plate and tent loosely with foil. ",
                      "type": "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text": "Rest",
                      "type": "text",
                      "marks": [
                        {
                          "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                          "attrs": {
                            "termId": "cmp73twkn0001p8v4kyryolap"
                          }
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "text": " for at least 30 minutes, up to 45 for a joint this size.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Carve across the grain into slices about 1 cm thick. The trivet vegetables and pan juices are the base of a red wine gravy.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "troubleshooter",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "fix": "Use a probe thermometer every time. Pull at 52 degrees C for rare to medium-rare. A 30-minute rest raises the core by about 3 to 5 degrees C, so factor that in.",
                "cause": "Overcooked, or the internal temperature climbed too high during resting.",
                "symptom": "The joint is grey throughout, not pink"
              },
              {
                "fix": "The minimum rest is 30 minutes; 45 is better for a joint this size. Keep the foil tent on.",
                "cause": "The joint was not rested long enough.",
                "symptom": "Juices pour out when carved"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Make sure the oven is fully up to temperature. Pat the surface completely dry before buttering.",
                "cause": "The oven was not hot enough at the start, or the joint surface was wet.",
                "symptom": "The surface is pale rather than browned"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Push the probe into the thickest part of the meat. Take two or three readings and go by the highest.",
                "cause": "Uneven thickness, or the probe is touching a fat seam rather than the muscle.",
                "symptom": "Probe readings vary across the joint"
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Variations",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "A rub of fresh horseradish mixed into the butter is a good alternative to mustard powder. Bone-in sirloin needs a slightly longer roast and a lower temperature because the bone conducts heat unevenly.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "The British Sunday roast is built around beef. Every cookbook from Mrs Beeton onward devotes pages to it, arguing over basting schedules and dripping versus butter. The sirloin is the prestige cut: more expensive than topside, leaner than rib, and well-suited to eating pink. It reached its current form in nineteenth-century domestic cooking and has not changed much since.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    "servings": 6,
    "yieldDescription": null,
    "difficulty": "INTERMEDIATE"
  },
